## ARTICLE II: Capital Contributions and Membership
 
### 2.1 Initial Capital
The Member has contributed 100% of the initial capital, intellectual property (including the codebase, design assets, and trademarks of abcAssess), and assets to the Company.
 
> *Note: This section is consistent with and supported by the abcAssess Intellectual Property Assignment Agreement executed on the same date. Both documents should be signed together.*
 
### 2.2 Percentage of Ownership
The Member owns 100% of the membership interests in the Company.
 
### 2.3 Limited Liability
The Member shall not be personally liable for any debts, obligations, or liabilities of the Company solely by reason of being a member or manager. The Company's liabilities are separate legal obligations of the Company entity alone.
 
---
 
## ARTICLE III: Management and Voting
 
### 3.1 Management
The Company shall be Manager-Managed. The Member hereby designates Danielle Andrist as the sole Manager. The Manager shall have full, exclusive, and complete authority, discretion, and control over the day-to-day operations and business decisions of the Company.
 
### 3.2 Authority
The Manager is authorized to sign contracts, bind the Company to legal obligations, open and maintain business bank accounts, obtain debt, and execute financial transactions on behalf of the Company.
 
### 3.3 Indemnification
The Company shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the Manager from and against any and all claims, liabilities, damages, costs, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys' fees) arising out of or relating to any act or omission taken in good faith on behalf of the Company in the Manager's capacity as Manager, except to the extent arising from the Manager's gross negligence, willful misconduct, or fraud.
 
### 3.4 Succession
In the event of the Member's death, permanent incapacity, or prolonged inability to act as Manager (as determined by a licensed physician), the Company's operations shall be managed by a successor designated in the Member's most recent written estate planning documents or, absent such designation, by the Member's legal personal representative. Such successor shall have authority to wind up the Company's affairs or continue operations, as determined in the sole discretion of the successor and the Member's estate.
 
---
 
## ARTICLE IV: Capital, Future Financing, and Investor Rights
 
### 4.1 Issuance of Future Equity and SAFE Notes
The Manager retains explicit authority to issue future financial instruments on behalf of the Company, including but not limited to Simple Agreements for Future Equity (SAFE Notes), convertible promissory notes, or regular equity interests to outside investors (including friends, family, or institutional investors). Any such issuance shall be documented in a written instrument signed by the Manager.
 
### 4.2 Retained Control
The issuance of future financial rights or equity shall not, under any circumstances, transfer or diminish the Manager's creative, technical, or operational control of the Company. Any amendment to this Agreement that would affect the Member's ownership percentage or the Manager's operational authority must be made in a separate written amendment executed by the Member pursuant to Section 7.1.
 
### 4.3 Anti-Dilution Protection
No issuance of future equity, SAFE Notes, convertible instruments, or any other financial instruments shall dilute the Member's voting or governance rights without the Member's prior written consent and a formal amendment to this Agreement. For the avoidance of doubt, economic dilution resulting from a validly documented investment round approved in writing by the Member is permitted, but the Member's operational and managerial authority shall not be diminished without explicit written consent.
 
### 4.4 Investor Rights Limitations
Investors who receive SAFE Notes, convertible notes, or future equity interests in the Company — unless otherwise expressly stated in a separate written agreement signed by the Manager — shall have no right to: (a) vote on any Company matter; (b) direct, interfere with, or participate in the management or operations of the Company; (c) access proprietary source code, design systems, or trade secrets of the Company; (d) demand distributions or returns of capital; or (e) transfer their interest to a third party without the Manager's prior written consent.
 
### 4.5 Right of First Refusal
In the event that any investor or holder of a financial instrument wishes to sell, transfer, assign, or otherwise dispose of their interest in the Company, the Member shall have the right of first refusal to purchase such interest at the same price and on the same terms as proposed by any third-party buyer. The investor must provide written notice to the Member of any proposed transfer, and the Member shall have thirty (30) days from receipt of such notice to exercise this right.
 
### 4.6 Dispute Resolution
Any dispute, claim, or controversy between the Company, the Member, the Manager, and any investor or holder of a financial instrument arising out of or relating to this Agreement or any investment instrument shall first be submitted to non-binding mediation before a mutually agreed-upon mediator. If mediation fails to resolve the dispute within sixty (60) days of initiation, either party may pursue any available legal remedy. The parties agree that any litigation shall be conducted exclusively in the courts of the State of North Dakota, and each party waives any objection to such venue.
 
